>
  <p>Most CRM programs do not fail because the enterprise picked the wrong platform. They fail because the platform never becomes part of how work actually moves.</p>
  <p>The system captures records. It stores activity. It gives leaders reporting. But the work still lives in email, meetings, spreadsheets, swivel-chair processes, local judgment, and informal escalation paths.</p>

  <blockquote>A system of record tells the enterprise what happened. A system of action changes what happens next.</blockquote>

  <h2>The record is not the work</h2>
  <p>Recording effort is not the same as improving work. If CRM does not clarify ownership, guide follow-up, surface risk, or make the next action easier, adoption becomes a compliance exercise.</p>
  <p>People enter data because they have to. Leaders get dashboards. The customer still feels the seams.</p>

  <h2>CRM data is often work exhaust</h2>
  <p>Activity data, notes, service history, ownership, relationship plans, and next steps are often captured after the work happened. That makes CRM useful for reporting, but weaker as a decision system.</p>
  <p>The opportunity is to turn CRM data into decision context: what matters now, what is unresolved, who owns it, and what action should happen next.</p>

  <h2>Where value leaks</h2>
  <p>Value leaks when customer context, workflow status, decision rights, and operating controls sit in different places. The associate has one view. The advisor has another. The manager has a dashboard. The client experiences the gaps.</p>
  <p>Modernization has to focus on the movement of work, not the beauty of the application.</p>

  <h2>What good looks like</h2>
  <p>CRM becomes useful when it helps the enterprise route work, prioritize action, capture evidence, reduce rework, and improve the quality of customer and associate experience.</p>
  <p>That requires data discipline, workflow design, adoption, governance, and a clear view of what outcome the system is meant to improve.</p>

  <h2>The executive test</h2>
  <p>The question is not whether the CRM has been deployed. The question is whether it has changed how work gets done.</p>
